               <p>THOMAS COWEN. I am a <rs id="t18280410-160-viclabel862" type="occupation">labourer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280410-160-victim949 t18280410-160-viclabel862"></join> at the King's Palace, St. James' Park. I was in <placeName id="t18280410-160-crimeloc863">Portman-street, Portman-square</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-160-crimeloc863" type="placeName" value="Portman-street, Portman-square"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280410-160-crimeloc863" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280410-160-off860 t18280410-160-crimeloc863"></join>, on the 17th of March; I had a handkerchief in my coat pocket - I did not feel it taken, but a crowd rushed up, about the baud of music, and I saw the prisoner put his hand under his apron - I thought he had<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182804100088"></xptr>something, and followed him out of crowd - the officer took him and took my handkerchief from under his apron.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280410-160-person950">
                  BENJAMIN 
                  IBBERSON
               <interp inst="t18280410-160-person950" type="surname" value="IBBERSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-160-person950" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280410-160-person950" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was passing through Portman-street; there was a mob round the soldiers going into the barracks, I saw the prisoner putting this handkerchief under his apron; the prosecutor came out of the crowd and identified it as his.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was going to look for work. My mother has six children; my father has been dead two years. A lad said to me "Go and take this handkerchief to the bottom of the street, and I will give you something" - it is my first offence.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 15.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18280410-160-verdict864" type="verdictDescription">
